The paper deals with the Moran process, which is a model for the spread of genetic mutations, and its extension to structured populations represented by graphs. This suggests that the paper could belong to the Discrete Mathematics (cs.DM) or Graph Theory (cs.GT) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper discusses the existence of families of graphs that act as strong amplifiers or suppressors of selection, which could fall under the Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) or Network Economics (cs.NE) sub-categories. Finally, the paper also presents graph constructions and upper bounds on the fixation probability, which could be relevant to the Computational Complexity (cs.CC) sub-category.
